 @Nug U   You dont need to be a "climate scientist" to understand why this video makes a lot of sense.... It's basic radiation physics (energy absorption / emission) combined with basic celestial mechanics. It lines up pretty well and is only complexified by the internal dynamics of earth's atmosphere.
"it more likely the sun went through a cooling cycle" ... That line shows exactly he has no understanding of physics. Celestial mechanics create much more precise cycles than any internal dynamics of the sun could ever generate. Of course, there are multiple overlapping cycles of varying periods and even some monotonic (i.e. non-periodic) dynamics on top (such as the moon moving away from the earth), so that the resulting characteristics generate some complexity. But we do have the mathematical tools to verify what has been said in this video to a significant degree. Large scale modulations generated by the movement and rotations of earth and other celestial bodies do not even have to cause climate cycles on their own. Stochastic resonance teaches us that such modulations may still need some intensity of noise on top of it to actually trigger a shift in climate. And the complex internal dynamics of the earth's atmosphere does provide exactly that in the form of chaotic dynamics. Depending on the intensity of this noise the resulting climate dynamics may or may not resonate quite well with the large scale modulations. If the noise intensity is too low, they can't cause shifts in climate. If it's too high, then shifts will appear more frequently, thus with less correlation to the periods of large scale modulations. If it's within a certain range, there will be a strong resonance with the large scale modulations.
However, I think radiation physics combined with celestial mechanics does provide a strong enough modulation to trigger these climate shifts on their own, especially given the positive feedback loops in each direction generated by the surface area of ice.

